Shakespeare makes this a satisfying moment in the play:
Intro:
    This moment serves as the beginning of the resolution, and marks an end to the chaos of the play
1. Resolves the tension between the four lysander, demetrius, hermia, helena, confirming that Oberon's "plan" to restore harmony has succeeded
    - The original couple we would have rooted for, lysander and hermia, are together, and this is no longer contested by demetrius
        - "my love to hermia melted as the snow, seems to me now as the remembrance of an idle gaud"
    Shakespeare uses language suggestive of union to create a sense of harmony, which is satisfying to the audience as it notes a rep
2.
    Egeus, the main "villain" in this part of the plot, who to the modern audience may be seen as cruel e.g. is defeated and humiliated
    - Egeus uses repetition "enough"; "the law"; righteously, and is overriden by both demetrius and theseus
3. The looming threat of Hermia's unwilling marriage is over


This moment of the play serves as the beginning of the resolution of the plot, and marks an end to the chaos of the prior plot. Here, the satisfaction of the moment is intertwined with its nature as the beginning of the resolution: it is satisfying because it makes clear steps towards resolving the chaotic plot-lines, and it makes for a good resolution because it is satisfying.

Firstly, Shakespeare in this moment resolves the tension between the four main characters: Lysander, demetrius, Hermia, and Helena. While in the previous act and scene they were at great odds with each other, here Shakespeare makes clear that they are harmonious and even friendly towards each other.

    

